{
  "text": "The nervous system expresses all of the enzymes required for steroid biosynthesis to produce a variety of neurosteroids. However, it is beyond the scope of this review to address effects and mechanisms of all neurosteroids. Our focus is on 3a,5a-THP. The peripheral-type benzodiazepine receptor (PBR), which is essential for neurosteroidogenesis, binds cholesterol in nanomolar affinities (Diagram 2). The PBR helps import cholesterol into the mitochondria, where it can be oxidized to pregnenolone by two proteins that initiate steroidogenesis--the steroidogenic acute regulatory (StAR) protein and cytochrome P450-dependent C27 side chain cleavage enzymes (P450scc), rate-limiting steps in steroid biosynthesis [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Once pregnenolone is synthesized from cholesterol by StAR and P450scc, several 3a-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase (3a-HSD) enzymes can convert the prohormones to neuroactive steroids. Key examples of neurosteroids/neuroactive steroids, which are derived from cholesterol and/or blood-borne precursors, respectively, are pregnenolone, which is converted to P, and its product, 5a-pregnane-3,20-dione-dihydroprogesterone, DHP), which can be converted to 3a,5a-THP and its 5b-stereoisomer (3a,5b-THP).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "14358830",
